intro: Tridactyle inaequilonga, commonly known as the unequal-stemmed tridactyle, is a species of flowering plant native to certain regions of South America. It belongs to the family Apiaceae, which includes many aromatic herbs and vegetables. The plant is characterized by its slender, branched stems and small, clustered flowers that typically bloom in the spring. Its leaves are pinnately divided, giving the plant a delicate, fern-like appearance. Tridactyle inaequilonga is often found in moist, shaded habitats and is of interest to botanists due to its unique morphological features.
